<glossary id="glossary-1">
    <title>Glossary</title>
    <glossentry id="glossary-6">
        <glossterm>applet</glossterm>
        <glossdef>
            <para>An applet is a small, interactive application that resides within a panel, for
                example the <application>CD Player</application>. Each applet has a simple user
                interface that you can operate with the mouse or keyboard. </para>
        </glossdef>
    </glossentry>
    <glossentry id="glossary-7">
        <glossterm>workspace</glossterm>
        <glossdef>
            <para>A workspace is a discrete area in the GNOME Desktop in which you can work. </para>
        </glossdef>
    </glossentry>
    <glossentry id="glossary-8">
        <glossterm>AFAIK</glossterm>
        <glossdef>
            <para>As Far As I Know</para>
        </glossdef>
    </glossentry>
    <glossentry id="filesystem">
        <glossterm>Filesystem</glossterm>
        <glossdef>
            <para>A way of storing files on a medium which can be hard drives, floppies, cdroms etc,etc...</para>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <guimenu>Ext3</guimenu> (3nd Extended) is currently the "native" FS for linux.</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <guimenu>ReiserFS</guimenu> is a recent filesystem, designed for both speed
                        and survivability.</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <guimenu>ISO9660</guimenu>Usually the standard for CD-ROMs.</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <guimenu>FAT &amp; VFAT</guimenu>The linux names for the standard
                        Microsoft(r) Windows(r) filesystems: fat16 (fat) and fat32 (vfat).</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <guimenu>SMB &amp; NFS</guimenu> Network filesystems, that allow
                        computers to share data. 'smb' is Microsoft(r)'s well-known 'Network Neighborhood'.</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                    <para>
                        <guimenu>PROC &amp; DEV</guimenu>Special filesystems</para>
                </listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
            <para>Linux supports a great number of other file systems, most of them with
                read/write-access, some with read-access only. </para>
        </glossdef>
    </glossentry>
</glossary>
